  "prompt": "How do I handle a simultaneous connections given to the host in nsurlsession?",
  "response": "To handle simultaneous connections in NSURLSession, you have several options depending on your specific requirements:\n\n1. Default Behavior with URLSession:\n```swift\n// By default, URLSession can handle multiple concurrent connections\nlet configuration = URLSessionConfiguration.default\nlet session = URLSession(configuration: configuration)\n\n// Multiple requests can be made simultaneously\nsession.dataTask(with: url1) { data, response, error in\n    // Handle first request\n}.resume()\n\nsession.dataTask(with: url2) { data, response, error in\n    // Handle second request\n}.resume()\n```\n\n2. Limit Concurrent Connections:\n```swift\nlet configuration = URLSessionConfiguration.default\nconfiguration.httpMaximumConnectionsPerHost = 5 // Limit to 5 concurrent connections\n\nlet session = URLSession(configuration: configuration)\n```\n\n3. Using OperationQueue for Controlled Concurrency:\n```swift\nclass NetworkManager {\n    private let session: URLSession\n    private let operationQueue: OperationQueue\n    \n    init() {\n        let configuration = URLSessionConfiguration.default\n        configuration.httpMaximumConnectionsPerHost = 5\n        \n        operationQueue = OperationQueue()\n        operationQueue.maxConcurrentOperationCount = 5 // Limit concurrent operations\n        \n        session = URLSession(configuration: configuration)\n    }\n    \n    func performMultipleRequests(urls: [URL]) {\n        urls.forEach { url in\n            let operation = BlockOperation {\n                let semaphore = DispatchSemaphore(value: 0)\n                \n                self.session.dataTask(with: url) { data, response, error in\n                    // Handle individual request\n                    semaphore.signal()\n                }.resume()\n                \n                // Wait for task to complete\n                semaphore.wait()\n            }\n            \n            operationQueue.addOperation(operation)\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n4. Async/Await Approach (iOS 15+):\n```swift\nclass NetworkManager {\n    private let session: URLSession\n    \n    init() {\n        let configuration = URLSessionConfiguration.default\n        configuration.httpMaximumConnectionsPerHost = 5\n        session = URLSession(configuration: configuration)\n    }\n    \n    func fetchData(urls: [URL]) async {\n        await withTaskGroup(of: Void.self) { group in\n            for url in urls {\n                group.addTask {\n                    do {\n                        let (data, response) = try await self.session.data(from: url)\n                        // Process data\n                    } catch {\n                        // Handle error\n                    }\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n5. Controlling with Dispatch Groups:\n```swift\nfunc performMultipleRequests(urls: [URL]) {\n    let group = DispatchGroup()\n    let queue = DispatchQueue(label: \"com.yourapp.networkqueue\", attributes: .concurrent)\n    \n    urls.forEach { url in\n        group.enter()\n        queue.async {\n            let task = URLSession.shared.dataTask(with: url) { data, response, error in\n                // Handle individual request\n                group.leave()\n            }\n            task.resume()\n        }\n    }\n    \n    group.notify(queue: .main) {\n        // All requests completed\n    }\n}\n```\n\nKey Considerations:\n- URLSession can naturally handle multiple concurrent connections\n- You can limit connections per host using `httpMaximumConnectionsPerHost`\n- Use OperationQueue or Dispatch Groups for more controlled concurrency\n- Async/Await provides a more modern approach to handling concurrent network requests\n\nBest Practices:\n- Set appropriate timeout intervals\n- Handle errors for each request\n- Consider network conditions and device capabilities\n- Use cancellation for long-running or unnecessary requests\n\nChoose the approach that best fits your specific use case and iOS deployment target.",
